In Java, something like @SomeText is called an annotation.

What does an annotation do?
    Annotations dont directly change how code runs. Instead, they:
        Give extra information to the compiler
        Help tools/frameworks (like Spring, Hibernate)
        Enable code generation / validation

Common Built-in Annotations
    @Override
    @Deprecated
    @SuppressWarnings
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Real Power: Framework Annotations
    In modern Java (especially backend), annotations drive everything.

    Example with Spring Boot:

        @RestController
        public class UserController {

            @GetMapping("/users")
            public String getUsers() {
                return "Users list";
            }
        }

    Here:
        @RestController → tells Spring this is a web controller
        @GetMapping     → maps HTTP GET request
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
you cant just “print” an annotation like a normal object. 
You have to read it using reflection at runtime.

Where this is actually used (real-world)
    Frameworks like Spring do exactly this internally:

            @RestController

    Spring:
        reads annotation via reflection
        then configures behavior
----------------------------------------------------------------------------